<span id="freeTextContainer2383424333034053845">This play is just amazing. It&apos;s harder to talk about things that were pretty much perfect but I will try. <br/><br/>There&apos;s a lot going on in this play. What made it so strong for me was how it combined both the drama of a couple dealing with trauma with the difficulties of the country, while talking about justice, repentance, forgiveness, culture, and gender roles. Somehow this play manages to get all of these down and more while developing each one. <br/><br/>It was so suspenseful, I picked it up and I couldn&apos;t s</span>
  <span id="freeText2383424333034053845" style="display:none">This play is just amazing. It's harder to talk about things that were pretty much perfect but I will try. <br /><br />There's a lot going on in this play. What made it so strong for me was how it combined both the drama of a couple dealing with trauma with the difficulties of the country, while talking about justice, repentance, forgiveness, culture, and gender roles. Somehow this play manages to get all of these down and more while developing each one. <br /><br />It was so suspenseful, I picked it up and I couldn't stop, it ruled my mind until I finished it. I was so intrigued by how the play-writer managed to get me to care so quickly. <br /><br />All in all, I'll probably reread this soon and I most definitely recommend this! <br /><br /><b> What I'm taking with me </b> <br />• Am I more like Paulina, Roberto or Gerardo? <br />• I just read a bit about Chile and wow, that is a country that has been through a lot. <br />• I would love to play Roberto in some adaption of this. </span>
