<div id="review_3839173221" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3839173221" />
    <a title="Charlie Lee" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/59034735-charlie-lee"><img alt="Charlie Lee" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1472281193p2/59034735.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3839173221?book_show_action=true">Feb 15, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Charlie Lee" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Charlie Lee" href="/user/show/59034735-charlie-lee">Charlie Lee</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781854593900" href="/book/show/249150.Death_And_The_Maiden">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59034735-charlie-lee?shelf=plays">plays</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3839173221" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14163243302778970368">3.5 stars. <br/><br/>I haven&apos;t read much by Dorfman, but the Pinteresque tribute at the beginning is fitting, though Pinter of The Hothouse and Birthday Party, rather than his later work. There&apos;s a huge amount of tension and action created between these three characters, which is escalated through some well-handled plot twists. There&apos;s even some irony in how the doctor came to be in his predicament. <br/><br/>If you&apos;re looking for a short play with a small cast, you could certainly do worse than Dorfman&apos;s Death and</span>
  <span id="freeText14163243302778970368" style="display:none">3.5 stars. <br /><br />I haven't read much by Dorfman, but the Pinteresque tribute at the beginning is fitting, though Pinter of The Hothouse and Birthday Party, rather than his later work. There's a huge amount of tension and action created between these three characters, which is escalated through some well-handled plot twists. There's even some irony in how the doctor came to be in his predicament. <br /><br />If you're looking for a short play with a small cast, you could certainly do worse than Dorfman's Death and The Maiden. This probably won't be your favourite play, but it's certainly entertaining. Quite a 'thriller', to use the terminology employed by the film industry, and probably pretty captivating to watch live. It's also fun to see a piece that's quite minimal in its set and cast requirements in an era somewhat dominated by big National Theatre productions.<br /><br />**EDIT** After listening to the LA Theatre Works production, I have reevaluated and am giving it 4 stars. The tension of the drama can't really be captured by the text. It's a play that should be watched / listened to. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14163243302778970368" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


