<div id="review_1937074824" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1937074824" />
    <a title="Aria" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32830977-aria"><img alt="Aria" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1587780814p2/32830977.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1937074824?book_show_action=true">Mar 09, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aria" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aria" href="/user/show/32830977-aria">Aria</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1937074824" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4269783200037218138">A play on the psychological aftereffects of the violation of human rights in a country emerging from totalitarian dictatorship, and to some extent, the cycles of violence. This play is a little confusing in the beginning but things clear up when more information is given. I find it clever that the characters can symbolize things and that the play can pretty much be set anywhere. However, I don’t really feel much for the characters despite their solid characterizations.</span>

          </span>
        </div>


