<div id="review_439596247" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/439596247" />
    <a title="Vincent" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1738263-vincent"><img alt="Vincent" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1227469968p2/1738263.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/439596247?book_show_action=true">Oct 22, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Vincent" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Vincent" href="/user/show/1738263-vincent">Vincent</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer439596247" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7723106247716403981">Having read this a decade ago, and seen the movie countless times, I was compelled to revisit this story for a number of reasons, not the least of which was my idea that it would be a good text to use in a class I am teaching. I&apos;ve since decided to use the film version instead, as I consider it a better execution of the tale and the themes (and because it is, in my mind, Polanski&apos;s best film since Chinatown). But that doesn&apos;t mean that this play isn&apos;t anything short of fantastic. <br/><br/>Outside of one </span>
  <span id="freeText7723106247716403981" style="display:none">Having read this a decade ago, and seen the movie countless times, I was compelled to revisit this story for a number of reasons, not the least of which was my idea that it would be a good text to use in a class I am teaching. I've since decided to use the film version instead, as I consider it a better execution of the tale and the themes (and because it is, in my mind, Polanski's best film since Chinatown). But that doesn't mean that this play isn't anything short of fantastic. <br /><br />Outside of one bit at the end involving a mirror facing the audience, forcing them to confront themselves and possibly implicating all of us, I loved the whole thing. That last conceit was a bit much, but theater is known for indulging such moments whereas, to the reader less versed in drama (like me), it can smack of pretension. Forgetting that one detail, this is top notch work. I still think the story found its perfect manifestation in Polanski's film, but the source material more than holds up. </span>
  <a data-text-id="7723106247716403981" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


