<div id="review_3374966143" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3374966143" />
    <a title="Trevor Kew" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7860789-trevor-kew"><img alt="Trevor Kew" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442515169p2/7860789.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3374966143?book_show_action=true">Jun 04, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Trevor Kew" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Trevor Kew" href="/user/show/7860789-trevor-kew">Trevor Kew</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7860789-trevor-kew?shelf=kew-f">kew-f</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3374966143" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2791971105495468383">As part of my push to read more IBDP drama texts, this play had been on my list for a very long time. Reading it was quite the experience; unusually for a play, you don&apos;t need to watch it live (or on film) for the intensity of its horror to absorb you. The dialogue of the characters and the pacing of the plot build so forcefully here that I forget I was reading a script. The play also portrays the complicated nature of justice in terms of revenge vs. reconciliation, reflecting the problems inher</span>
  <span id="freeText2791971105495468383" style="display:none">As part of my push to read more IBDP drama texts, this play had been on my list for a very long time. Reading it was quite the experience; unusually for a play, you don't need to watch it live (or on film) for the intensity of its horror to absorb you. The dialogue of the characters and the pacing of the plot build so forcefully here that I forget I was reading a script. The play also portrays the complicated nature of justice in terms of revenge vs. reconciliation, reflecting the problems inherent with either approach. It's one of those great literary texts that leaves you unsure which way is right (or if either way is right, or if there is ever a right way) to respond to horrific injustice. At this particular time in history (June 2020), reading this play was a powerful reminder that responding to injustice is never simple whether we take the emotional response (revenge!) or rational approach (endless and often unsatisfying "commissions/enquiries").<br /><br />While Dorfman is Chilean and cultural references (margaritas, etc.) put this text in that country (or at least that region), the personal way the story is related here is clearly relevant to so many contexts (post-Nazi Nuremberg, Tokyo Trials, Rwanda, and the current troubles in America). A fascinating read. I might check out the Polanski film...seems like a good one?</span>
  <a data-text-id="2791971105495468383" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


